Tinker 4: RepairSafe
Most LLM applications aren't just "send question, get answer." In high-stakes domains — medicine, finance, legal advice, home repair — a confident LLM answer can cause real harm if it's wrong. The pattern that handles this isn't more capability; it's a safety layer that classifies each request before the main model responds.

Today you'll build that layer. RepairSafe is a home repair Q&A assistant with a three-tier classification system: safe (routine DIY), caution (doable but risky), and refuse (professional required). Before the assistant answers any question, it determines which tier the repair belongs to — and adjusts its behavior accordingly.

The core technical challenge is prompt precision. Classifying "how do I replace a faucet?" and "how do I add a new outlet to my garage?" sounds similar, but these questions are in completely different tiers. The first is a component swap at an existing location — no permit, recoverable if wrong. The second requires opening the electrical panel, running new wire, and obtaining a permit — the amateur mistake here creates a fire hazard that may not be discovered for years. Your classifier needs to make this distinction reliably, which means your prompt needs to define the boundary precisely enough that the LLM applies it consistently.

This is how content moderation, safety filtering, and guardrails work in production AI systems.

🎯 Goals
By completing this activity, you will be able to:

Design a multi-tier safety classifier using an LLM-as-judge pattern.
Write a system prompt that prevents dangerous instructions without making the assistant useless.
Implement an append-only audit log in the .jsonl format used in production AI systems.
Explain why the caution/refuse boundary is the most consequential classification decision in a safety layer.

🪄 How this works: Work together as a group throughout the activity using the Driver/Navigator model. The Driver shares their screen and implements the solution while Navigators help guide decisions, ask questions, discuss tradeoffs, and troubleshoot challenges. At each checkpoint, pause to reflect on your group's progress, discuss key implementation decisions, and make sure everyone understands the solution before moving on.
