Milestone 1: Build the Safety Classifier
⏰ ~20 min

The classifier is the most important component in this pipeline. If it misclassifies a refuse-tier question as caution, the responder will provide instructions it shouldn't. Getting the tier boundaries right — in the prompt — is the whole job.

🧠 Before You Start
📔 LLM-as-Judge

In most of this course, you've used LLMs to generate output for end users — answers, instructions, advice. This milestone flips that: you're using an LLM to make a structured decision that the system consumes, not the user. That's the LLM-as-judge pattern.

The "judge" isn't being asked to be helpful or creative. It's being asked to evaluate input against a set of criteria and return a classification. Your classifier call looks like: "Given this home repair question and these tier definitions, which tier is it?" The output goes straight into your pipeline logic — if tier == "refuse": ... — not to the user.

This pattern shows up everywhere in production AI: OpenAI's Moderation API runs a classifier before the main model responds. Automated content review pipelines use LLM judges to score text at scale. Quality evaluation systems use LLMs to rate output before it's accepted. In all of these cases, the same principle applies: the quality of the classifier depends almost entirely on how precisely the prompt defines the decision criteria.

What "precise" means here: vague criteria produce inconsistent output. If your prompt says "classify risky questions as caution," the LLM has to interpret "risky" — and it will interpret it differently on different questions. Precise criteria name the actual boundary condition in terms the LLM can apply mechanically: "If an amateur mistake could cause fire, flooding, structural failure, injury, or death → refuse." That's a rule, not a vibe.

The output format matters too. Your classifier needs to return something your code can parse reliably. If the LLM returns Tier: caution\nReason: ..., your parser needs to extract "caution" and validate it against VALID_TIERS. An LLM might return "Refuse" with a capital R, or wrap the tier in quotes, or add a colon after it — normalize and validate before the tier value touches your pipeline logic.

📔 Safety Classification Tiers

The three-tier model gives the system useful resolution across a wide spectrum of repairs. Here's the logic behind why three tiers, and what makes the boundaries meaningful:

Why not two tiers (safe/unsafe)? A binary split loses the middle. "Replace a faucet" and "replace an electrical panel" are both technically "unsafe" if unsafe means "has some risk" — but they're completely different in practice. The caution tier captures repairs that are genuinely doable for a motivated homeowner but where a mistake has real cost. Without it, the system either over-refuses (unhelpfully blocking faucet replacements) or under-refuses (helpfully walking someone through panel work).

The caution/refuse boundary — the decision rule: Ask one question: if this repair goes wrong, can it cause fire, flooding, structural failure, injury, or death? If yes: refuse. If the worst case is a leaky pipe or a broken fixture: caution.

The most important edge case — "replacing existing" vs. "adding new" in electrical work:

Question	Tier	Why
"How do I replace an outlet that stopped working?"	caution	Existing circuit, same location, component swap — worst case is a tripped breaker
"How do I add a new outlet to my garage?"	refuse	Requires opening the panel, running new wire, pulling a permit — amateur mistake = fire hazard discovered years later
The component is the same (an outlet), but one repairs an existing installation and the other creates new electrical infrastructure. Your classifier prompt needs to make this distinction explicit.

Framing doesn't change the tier. A user who says "I just want to move my switch six inches — it's a tiny change" is still describing refuse-tier work. Moving the switch requires running new wire to the new location. Classify based on what the repair actually requires, not how the user has described it.


