Milestone 3: Build the Audit Logger
⏰ ~10 min

The classifier and responder make the system useful. The audit logger makes it accountable. Production AI applications in high-stakes domains are expected to produce a record of what they said and why — so that if something goes wrong, you can reconstruct exactly what happened.

🧠 Before You Start
📔 Audit Logging and the JSONL Format

Audit logs aren't just for debugging — they're the accountability layer that makes a production AI system trustworthy. In high-stakes domains, "the model decided to answer that way" is not an acceptable explanation if something goes wrong. A log is what lets you reconstruct exactly what happened: what was the question, what tier did the classifier assign, what did the model say, and when.

Logs also catch systematic errors you'd never catch from individual user reports. If your classifier is consistently misclassifying a certain type of question, you won't know until you see the pattern across hundreds of entries. Individual users usually don't report classification errors — they just get a bad answer and leave.

The JSONL format. JSONL (JSON Lines) stores one JSON object per line — each record is a complete, independently parseable unit:

{"timestamp": "2025-11-01T14:22:01", "tier": "refuse", "question": "How do I add a new outlet...", "response_preview": "This type of electrical work..."}
{"timestamp": "2025-11-01T14:23:18", "tier": "safe", "question": "How do I patch a small hole...", "response_preview": "Patching small drywall holes..."}
This is different from regular JSON (a single object or array with indentation). JSONL has specific advantages for logging:

Append-only: you add one line per event — you never rewrite the whole file
Independently parseable: a corrupted line doesn't break the rest of the file
Works with log aggregation tools (Splunk, Datadog, CloudWatch) without transformation — these tools expect one-record-per-line
Memory-efficient at scale: you can process a 10GB log file line by line without loading it all into memory
Practical note: use json.dumps() to serialize your record and write it with "\n". Don't use json.dump() with indent= — that produces multi-line pretty-printed JSON, which breaks the JSONL format and makes the file unparseable by log tools.

What fields to log: Required fields (timestamp, tier, question, response_preview) get you started. Think about what a developer reviewing 10,000 entries would actually need to diagnose a problem — not just what happened, but enough signal to filter, group, and identify patterns.


